# Agent orchestration and escalation

- **User-requested agent = real dispatch, not persona:** When the user explicitly asks to **use / invoke / run / call / Task** a named agent, the parent assistant **must** **`Task`** that agent (see **`mode-auto-selection.mdc`** — explicit invocation gate). **Never** substitute in-chat imitation of that agent’s output style for a missing **`Task`**.

- **Task-first tool contract (parent chat — non-negotiable):** When **`mode-auto-selection`** says the user **invoked** an agent (including **delegate / assign / hand off / orchestrate with** patterns), the **parent** session **must** emit **`Task`** with matching **`subagent_type`** **before** any **mutating** tool on workspace repos for that request. **Violations** (implementing P1–Pn, “I'll handle this phase,” or editing product paths **before** dispatch) are **routing failures** — **stop**, **admit the miss**, **`Task`** the named agent with the original brief, **do not** duplicate the child’s owned work in parallel prose. **Entrypoints** (`cto`, `tech-lead`, `code-reviewer`, `n8n-builder`, `remotion-builder`, `atlassian-pm`, `cro-loop` targets, etc.) **never** get main-chat **substitute execution**.

- **Subagent orchestration — zero-gap (hard):** A **hop** = one **`Task`** completion (or explicit protocol **`malformed`/`degraded`** stub) before the parent claims that agent’s work. **No gap** means: (1) **every** specialist/implementer output the user sees as “from agent X” was produced by a **`Task`** to X (or a single allowed orchestrator synthesis step that **only** merges verbatim structured fields per **`subagent-response-protocol`** — no new facts); (2) **no** parent turn interleaves **mutating** product edits with **unfulfilled** child dispatches for the same scope; (3) **`cto`**, **`tech-lead`**, **`code-reviewer`**, and **`cro-loop`** internals treat missing child **`Task`** the same as a **routing failure** — **do not** pad with main-chat substitutes; (4) parallel **`Task`** shards: **disjoint `touches[]` only** — if overlap sneaks in, **stop** and redelegate (see **`parallel-dispatch`** / anti-dup hook). **Impersonation** of a child agent in parent chat = **always** a violation, even if the prose “matches” the plan.

- **Start with `cto` in plan mode** when a task has multiple steps, non-trivial trade-offs, or touches architecture, security, performance, or observability.
- **Start with `code-reviewer`** for any code review request — PR links, branches, diffs, "review my change", security/perf/style review. It is the single entry point for review just as `cto` is for planning: it applies an adaptive context gate (full context for external/author review, lightweight context for same-cycle `tech-lead` feedback loops), then triages and delegates to org specialists. `staff-engineer` is mandatory in review routing. Never invoke `vp-architecture`/`ciso`/`vp-engineering`/`sre-lead`/`staff-engineer`/`vp-platform` directly for review — go through `code-reviewer`.
- **Invoker-wins precedence (R10):**
  - **`staff-engineer`**: for direct, single-shot implementation when **no** orchestration is required — work is small/localized, there is **no** multi-step **plan** (phased / verification blocks), **no** project team under `.cursor/agents/`, **single** workspace root, and the user did not request cross-root or phased orchestration. If **`staff-engineer`** (or any agent) publishes a **phased plan**, **execution-boundary critic** applies before implementation — **`Task` `cto`** to run **`cro-loop`** (surrogate) when that agent cannot run the loop itself.
  - **`tech-lead`**: when **any** orchestration signal is true: (a) `cto` plan with a phase graph, (b) project team present in `.cursor/agents/`, (c) task spans **≥ 2** workspace roots, (d) **explicit user request** to use `tech-lead` or to orchestrate across folders/phases.
  - **Invoker wins**: if the user names an agent, honor that agent. If the user describes work without naming an agent → choose `tech-lead` when **any** of the four signals above holds; otherwise `staff-engineer`.
- **Use `vp-onboarding`** to bootstrap or refresh project-local agents, rules, and skills in a repo's `.cursor/` directory; never modify org-level agents from project agents.
- **Default modes:** `cto` and other org VPs run in plan mode; `code-reviewer` runs in Agent (read-only review) mode; `staff-engineer` runs in Agent (implementation/review) mode by default; `tech-lead` runs in Agent mode **scoped to orchestration** — it **coordinates** approved-plan execution via `Task` to implementers, aggregates subagent results, and enforces checkpoints; it is **read-only on product repositories** (no direct code/config edits in app trees). See **`tech-lead-implementation-boundary.mdc`**. All project-level `dev-*`, `sme-*`, `qa-*`, and `devops` agents run in Agent (implementation) mode by default and only escalate to `cto` for a new plan when they discover architectural or multi-phase scope.

- **Org vs project responsibilities**
  - Org agents (`cto`, `cro`, `code-reviewer`, `vp-research`, `vp-architecture`, `vp-engineering`, `ciso`, `sre-lead`, `staff-engineer`, `vp-platform`, `tech-lead`, `atlassian-pm`) own cross-project strategy, plans, reviews, and high-level standards. Org-tier execution orchestration is defined in [`tech-lead`](../agents/tech-lead.md).
  - Project agents (`dev-*`, `sme-*`, `qa`, `devops`) own implementation and project-scoped specialization inside a specific repo, following org standards and project rules.
  - Project agents escalate up to org agents via `cto` (for plans) or `code-reviewer` (for reviews) when decisions affect architecture, security posture, performance budgets, or shared tooling.

- **Atlassian operations** (Jira / Confluence / Bitbucket) are owned by `atlassian-pm` globally. There is **no** project-level `pm-*`, `jira-*`, `confluence-*`, or `atlassian-*` agent. **No agent except `atlassian-pm` may call `plugin-atlassian-atlassian` write tools** (`createJiraIssue`, `editJiraIssue`, `transitionJiraIssue`, `addCommentToJiraIssue`, `addWorklogToJiraIssue`, `createIssueLink`, `createConfluencePage`, `updateConfluencePage`, `createConfluenceFooterComment`, `createConfluenceInlineComment`).
  - **Atlassian entry point (`atlassian-pm`) — WRITES:** the user explicitly requests Jira / Confluence / Bitbucket activity → invoke `atlassian-pm`. Never auto-trigger for writes. Every write is gated by draft-then-approve with a 5-minute approval expiry.
  - **Atlassian entry point (`atlassian-pm`) — READS:** any global org agent in the allow-list (`cto`, `cro`, `code-reviewer`, `vp-architecture`, `vp-engineering`, `ciso`, `sre-lead`, `staff-engineer`, `vp-platform`, `vp-onboarding`, `vp-research`) MAY invoke `atlassian-pm` via the Task tool with `mode=read-only-context` for planning / design / review context lookups. The allow-list is exhaustive; deny-by-default applies to any agent not listed. The broker preflights plugin + auth and returns `{ status: 'skipped', reason: ... }` on miss; callers MUST treat this as a silent no-op (no user-facing error). **Project-level agents** (`dev-*`, `sme-*`, `qa-*`, `devops`) are **NOT** in the allow-list and MUST always route through explicit user invocation. The deny-list is enforced before the allow-list. **Writes are still hard-gated to user invocation only** — `read-only-context` cannot escalate to a write session; the mode parameter cannot be flipped mid-session.
  - **Deprecated plugin skills (route through `atlassian-pm`):** `spec-to-backlog`, `triage-issue`, `capture-tasks-from-meeting-notes`, `generate-status-report`. Other agents must NOT invoke these plugin skills directly; they recommend `atlassian-pm` to the user. The plugin skill files at `~/.cursor/plugins/cache/cursor-public/atlassian/.../skills/<name>/SKILL.md` are upstream-managed and not edited; this is rule-level deprecation. The plugin skills remain available for direct user invocation if the user prefers, but the org policy is that agent-mediated Atlassian work routes through `atlassian-pm`.

- **Memory:** All agents follow `brain-conventions` and use `brain-memory-kb` (`mode: memory`) for reads and writes.
- **KB duty (entrypoints + decision writers):** **`cto`**, **`tech-lead`**, **`n8n-builder`**, **`remotion-builder`**, **`atlassian-pm`**, and org **`vp-*` / `ciso` / `sre-lead` / `staff-engineer` / `vp-platform` / `vp-onboarding`** when executing routed work **must** persist to **`~/ai-brain/`** **gradually** per **`brain-conventions.mdc` → Entrypoint + decision agents — KB duty** (per-repo **`kb-identity`**, phase-boundary writes, **`~/ai-brain`** pull/commit/push when it is a git clone). **`code-reviewer`** / **`cro`** hand off **`memory_writes[]`** — no direct brain writes.

- **Docs research:** All agents delegate documentation and web research to `vp-research`. **`vp-research.mdc`** is the canonical broker text.

- **Call-chain boundaries**
  - **Planning episode:** Any **multi-step / phased plan** from **any** org or project agent — not only `cto` — including `n8n-builder`, `remotion-builder`, consolidated `vp-*` swarm output, etc. **Plan artifact** = **persisted** path (e.g. `<project>/.cursor/docs/plans/*.md` or builder plan path per skill) **or** **prompt-only** (final plan text only in chat: user forbids disk, transient scope, no `<project>` yet). **Prefer** persisting v0 and post-critic revisions when possible; **critic still runs** on prompt-only text (stable excerpt in `Task` payload + ledger).
  - **Post–plan v0 edit round:** After **plan v0** is settled (disk or chat), the **planning-episode owner** asks **once** whether to add/remove/change anything; optional iterations. **No** “approve v0 for CRO” phrase.
  - **Execution-boundary critic (mandatory):** On **implement / execute / proceed with implementation** (or equivalent), the **planning-episode owner** MUST run the **singleton two-pass critic** **immediately** — **before** **`tech-lead`**, **`staff-engineer`**, or other implementers **and** before product mutations for that plan. **Tech default:** **`cro-loop`** (`cro` ×2; owner patches v1/v2). **Builders:** `n8n-builder` / `remotion-builder` use **their** mandated critic (same singleton + fail-closed) per planning-gate skills. **Not interleaved** with initial v0 drafting. **`cro` / critics** never write plan files; **owner** applies edits (disk and/or in-session). **`cro`** MUST apply the **full structured adversarial rubric** in **`cro-loop`** (**conditional depth** per plan complexity per **`cro`** / skill), not impressionistic expansion alone.
  - **Surrogate:** If the author cannot run the loop, **`Task` `cto`** (or assume `cto` ownership) to run **`cro-loop`** on the plan ref/text **before** execution.
  - **Fail-closed:** Missing/blocked/malformed pass 2 after retry → no execution authorization, no execution-mode choices. Override: **`"skip CRO loop for this plan"`** recorded in **`## Open Risks`** (stricter builder overrides per builder policy).
  - **Ledger:** `~/ai-brain/session/cursor-<task-id>/critic-ledger.md` (Cursor; OR-09). Gemini editorial: `~/ai-brain/session/gemini-<task-id>/critic-ledger.md`.
  - **Typical tech flow:** user → owner (`cto` most often) → v0 + edit round → execution intent → **`cro-loop`** → execution gate → **`tech-lead`** → implementers. Planning swarms may use **`Task`** parallelism where the owner allows.
  - For code review: the user → `code-reviewer` → context pass (commit history/diff/issue docs) → org specialists (in parallel, with mandatory `staff-engineer`) → synthesized review.
  - `tech-lead` is single entrypoint for execution + multi-root orchestration; users avoid direct `dev-*` for plan-bound work unless `tech-lead` routes there. Review-only bypasses `tech-lead`.

- **Planning vs execution boundary:** After **v0** (+ post–v0 edits) is **agreed** — on disk under `<project>/.cursor/docs/plans/` **or** **prompt-only** in session — the **planning-episode owner** may stop for planning-only work. **`tech-lead`** / implementers run only after **`cro-loop`** (or builder critic) yields **v2** on disk **and/or** **final in-session text** for prompt-only plans (or documented skip). On execution intent, owner runs critic first, then **two-choice execution gate** where applicable: **`phase-by-phase`**, **`all-phases-approved`**. Silence ≠ approval.
- **Single-entry hardening:** **`cto`** (default tech planning), **`code-reviewer`** (review), **`tech-lead`** (execution) are non-bypass routes. Do not emulate critic/execution gates inline. **Exception:** **`cto`** may run **`cro-loop`** as **surrogate** for another author’s plan. Precondition failure → fail-closed.

- **`remotion-builder` (user-invoked and content-handoff only):** `cto`, `tech-lead`, `staff-engineer`, `code-reviewer`, `vp-*`, `sre-lead`, `ciso`, `vp-platform`, `vp-onboarding`, and other **tech-pack** orchestrators **must not** `Task` `remotion-builder`. **No exception** from tech peers for convenience routing. **Cross-pack:** the **content org** may satisfy **`video-editor-handoff`** and then `Task` `remotion-builder` only when **`content-lead`** / explicit user rules in the **content** `agent-orchestration` allow it (plan-gated phase, or user naming the tech agent); **`cco`** only when the user explicitly asks **`cco`** to dispatch **`remotion-builder`** in planning — **not** from routing-table classification alone. **`sme-*`** must **not** `Task` `remotion-builder` directly.
- **Internal worker (`kokoro-audio-builder`):** **`remotion-builder`** **may** **`Task` `kokoro-audio-builder`** as a **serial Stage C worker** when **`video-editor-handoff`** sets **`audio.pipeline: kokoro_whisper_v1`** (and **`handoff_schema_version: 2`**). **No** other agent **`Task`s `kokoro-audio-builder`** except **`user`** lab/debug per **`kokoro-audio-builder-governance.mdc`**. Content-org **`Task` allowlist** to **`remotion-builder`** is unchanged.

- **No peer delegation:** Specialists / project agents NEVER `Task`-call each other laterally — always through `cto`, `tech-lead`, or `code-reviewer` orchestrator nodes.
  - **Exemption:** `cro` proposes specialist **bounce targets**; **only the planning-episode owner** (`cto`, `n8n-builder`, `remotion-builder` per their gates, …) may `Task` those specialists and merge replies. `cro` MUST NOT subagent-call `vp-*` / `ciso` / `sre-lead` / `staff-engineer` directly.

- **When to escalate to specialists (via `cto` for planning, via `code-reviewer` for review)**
  - `vp-architecture`: new services, significant refactors, data-model or boundary changes, cross-service contracts.
  - `ciso`: auth flows, secret management, input validation on public endpoints, CI/CD or container security.
  - `vp-engineering`: concurrency, retries, connection pools, queueing, performance regressions on hot paths.
  - `sre-lead`: logging, metrics, tracing, health checks, rollout/rollback strategy, SLO/SLA questions.
  - `staff-engineer`: large refactors, de-tangling complex modules, naming/structure changes with wide impact.
  - `vp-platform`: repeated patterns that suggest templates, CLIs, generators, or shared libraries.

- **Code review entry point (`code-reviewer`)**
  - The user gives a PR link, branch, or diff → invoke `code-reviewer`.
  - `code-reviewer` creates an isolated git worktree (for PR links) under `~/.cursor/worktrees/<repo>/pr-<N>-<sha>/`, never disturbing the user's current branch.
  - `code-reviewer` reads context first (commit intent/history + diff + linked specs), then triages and delegates in parallel to the relevant org specialists, always including `staff-engineer`.
  - `code-reviewer` synthesizes one unified review with severity-graded findings, style compliance against the repo's tools (and language-idiomatic fallbacks), and concrete optimization suggestions.
  - The review is always persisted to `<project>/.cursor/docs/reviews/YYYY-MM-DD-<slug>.md` (follows `docs-and-decisions`). **`<project>`** is the repo under review (worktree target or primary workspace root), not `~/.cursor/docs/`.
  - `code-reviewer` is **read-only** — it never modifies the codebase, pushes to remotes, or comments/approves on PRs unless the user explicitly asks.

- **Plan and phase discipline**
  - In plan mode, `cto` groups work into numbered phases with explicit verification and rollback for each phase.
  - Implementers (`dev-*`, `qa-*`, `devops`, or `staff-engineer` fallback), **coordinated** by `tech-lead` when orchestration applies (`tech-lead` does **not** implement), must:
    - Follow phases in order.
    - Run the specified verification for each phase before claiming it complete.
    - Stop and wait for explicit user approval at every checkpoint before moving to the next phase.

- **User approval semantics**
  - "Explicit user approval" at a checkpoint means the user uses the approval wording in the plan (for example replying with **"proceed"** as instructed) or an equally clear statement that the next phase may begin.
  - Silence, unrelated conversation, side questions, or generic praise must **never** be treated as approval to move to the next phase by `staff-engineer`, `dev-*`, `sme-*`, or `qa` agents. Org-tier `tech-lead` likewise must not infer approval from silence or generic praise at group checkpoints.

- **Division of labor during implementation**
  - `cto` and VPs: design the plan and define phases, risks, and verification.
  - `code-reviewer`: owns review triage, specialist delegation, and review synthesis.
  - `staff-engineer` / project `dev-*`: implement the plan with minimal diffs, matching existing patterns.
  - `tech-lead`: maps plan phases to project agents (per workspace folder), **`Task`-dispatches** work, tracks progress, merges structured child outputs for the user, and enforces checkpoints across roots — **no** product-tree edits (orchestration-only).
  - `staff-engineer`: default maintainability reviewer and fallback implementer when project-level implementers are absent. May consult project `sme-*` through orchestrated routing for domain-specific context.
  - Specialists (`ciso`, `sre-lead`, etc.): review or extend the plan/implementation only inside their domain.

- **Swarm + anti-duplication:** Disjoint `touches[]` parallelism + bounded background `Task` when no dependency / clarification blockers (`parallel-dispatch`, `routing-table.yml`). Deterministic merges use stable shard ordering + schemas in `templates/agent-result-bundle.yml.tmpl`. Payload caps + refs in `templates/subagent-response.yml.tmpl`; hook `./hooks/subagent-task-antidup-preflight.sh` + policy `configurations/orchestration-policies/anti-dup.yml`; audit `~/ai-brain/org/global/orchestration/dispatch-audit.md`.

- **Golden rule**
  - Every agent respects its scope, escalates instead of guessing outside that scope, and never skips plan checkpoints without explicit user instruction.
  - Every agent keeps its own context lean by following `brain-memory-kb` for memory operations instead of loading heavy skills and rules into every agent.
  - Every subagent → parent response follows `subagent-response-protocol` (structured YAML envelope, hooks-enforced). See `~/.cursor/rules/subagent-response-protocol.mdc`.

